The mechanism would use real-time metrics such as gradient inconsistency, local loss trajectory, and lightweight influence score approximations to assess client contribution quality. Additionally, contextual metadata from autonomous driving environments (e.g., weather, scene complexity) would inform a *context-aware client evaluator* to predict meaningful participation.

A novel component is a co-trained *client health monitor* using self-supervised contrastive learning on gradient embeddings to detect anomalies—such as mislabeled data or sensor drift—beyond simple performance drops. This system enhances FL efficiency, safety, and trustworthiness, aligning with expertise in robust ML and simulation-based validation, and offers strong potential for impactful research at the intersection of trustworthy AI and embodied intelligence.
