{
  "Idea": "We propose Probing-Aware Federated Learning with Contextual Contrastive Diagnosis (PA-FL/CCD), a novel framework designed to actively identify low-performing or data-inefficient clients in autonomous driving simulations by injecting lightweight, context-preserving perturbations into the global model before local training. Unlike passive monitoring approaches that rely solely on post-hoc analysis of update magnitude or loss trends, PA-FL/CCD introduces a proactive diagnostic phase where each communication round begins with the server broadcasting two variants of the global model: (1) the standard model, and (2) a semantically perturbed 'probe model' generated via contextual contrastive augmentation—e.g., slight domain shifts simulating foggy-night conditions synthesized from the client’s previously reported operational context. Clients train both models locally for one epoch and return both updates. The server then computes a \u00b4response divergence score\u00b4 between the two updates using Wasserstein distance in gradient space, normalized by client context rarity. High divergence indicates instability likely due to poor data quality or overfitting, while low divergence suggests robustness. Crucially, clients facing rare contexts (e.g., heavy rain + pedestrian crossing) are expected to show higher divergence initially; thus, we integrate a temporal smoothing filter and a causal attention module that disentangles whether divergence stems from \u00b4context novelty\u00b4 (valuable) vs. \u00b4intrinsic fragility\u00b4 (harmful). This is achieved via a meta-anomaly detector trained on historical divergence-context pairs across simulation episodes. Updates from fragile clients are down-weighted or rejected, while those from contextually rare but stable clients are up-weighted and used to enrich synthetic scenario pools. A second innovation is the use of a self-supervised Siamese probe encoder at the server that learns to generate maximally informative perturbations by minimizing mutual information between divergent and convergent client responses in a contrastive objective. This creates an adaptive 'stress-testing' protocol for FL participants. In autonomous driving, where silent failures (e.g., mislabeling occluded cyclists) are catastrophic, PA-FL/CCD enables early detection of flawed clients before they degrade the global model. We further demonstrate how detected anomalies can trigger targeted re-labeling requests or recalibration protocols in simulation environments, forming a closed-loop system for data curation. Evaluated in CARLA with heterogeneous fleets, PA-FL/CCD outperforms static exclusion and passive weighting methods in both convergence stability and rare-event recall.",
