Both Idea 0 (DynaCHF) and Idea 1 (PA-FL/CCD) exhibit high novelty, clarity, and feasibility, proposing sophisticated mechanisms for identifying and handling low-performing clients in federated learning (FL) for autonomous driving simulations. However, when assessing against existing literature, we must determine which idea introduces a more distinct and under-explored technical contribution.

Paper 5 (CAFL) is directly relevant to Idea 0, as it introduces Contribution-Aware Federated Learning, which evaluates client contributions without accessing raw data—precisely the direction of dynamic client assessment. While CAFL focuses on healthcare, its core idea of contribution evaluation based on update impact overlaps conceptually with DynaCHF’s use of influence functions and adaptive weighting. Moreover, the notion of modeling client “health” using training dynamics and context has parallels in existing FL robustness methods (e.g., FedProx, FedCD), and the dual-teacher architecture appears inspired by FedCD’s causal disentanglement approach, as acknowledged in both ideas.

In contrast, Idea 1 (PA-FL/CCD) introduces a *proactive diagnostic mechanism* via *contextual model probing*—a significantly more novel paradigm. The idea of injecting perturbed global models ("probe models") to elicit differential responses from clients and measuring response divergence as a signal of fragility vs. contextual novelty has no clear precedent in the provided papers. While Paper 1 (CARLA-FLMon) discusses monitoring and excluding poor clients, it does so via passive observation, not active intervention. PA-FL/CCD’s use of a self-supervised Siamese probe encoder to generate maximally informative perturbations through a contrastive objective adds another layer of innovation, effectively creating an adaptive stress-testing protocol—an idea not seen in any of the related work.

Furthermore, the integration of detected anomalies into synthetic scenario generation forms a closed-loop system that goes beyond mere client filtering, linking FL diagnostics to simulation design. This systems-level feedback is particularly valuable in safety-critical domains like autonomous driving.

While both ideas are strong, **Idea 1** demonstrates greater departure from existing literature, introducing a *causal, probing-based diagnosis* rather than building incrementally on known contribution evaluation frameworks. Its methodology is not only novel but also enables earlier, more accurate detection of inefficient clients before they harm the global model—addressing a critical gap in FL safety.

